\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Audit Planning and Annual Schedule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall approve an Annual Audit Plan no later than thirty (30) calendar days after the beginning of each fiscal year.
 The Assistant IT Director shall prepare the draft plan and submit it to the IT Director for review.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Annual Audit Plan shall identify,
 at minimum:
 the policies,
 controls,
 and processes to be assessed during the fiscal year;
 the assessment method for each item (internal audit,
 self-assessment,
 or control test);
 the planned quarter of execution;
 and the personnel or role responsible for conducting each assessment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Audit scope shall be determined on a risk-informed basis.
 The following factors shall inform prioritization:
 the results of the previous year's audit and assessment cycle,
 the risk ratings maintained under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Risk Management Policy),
 any open deficiencies tracked under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:5.03"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Compliance Monitoring and Corrective Action),
 changes to the regulatory or threat environment,
 and the results of any external audits or assessments conducted during the prior period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Every policy in the ECIO Policy Manual shall be assessed through at least one of the three mechanisms defined in this policy —
 internal audit,
 self-assessment,
 or control test —
 within each annual cycle.
 Policies governing controls subject to CJIS Security Policy obligations shall be assessed no less than annually through internal audit or control testing;
 self-assessment alone does not satisfy the CJIS assessment requirement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Annual Audit Plan is a planning instrument;
 it does not prevent the IT Director from authorizing additional assessments during the fiscal year.
 The IT Director may initiate unplanned audits in response to cybersecurity incidents,
 enforcement actions,
 external audit findings,
 regulatory changes,
 or risk conditions identified under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The Assistant IT Director shall document unplanned audits in the System of Engagement with the same rigor as planned audits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Self-Assessment Procedures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Self-assessments are process-owner evaluations that determine whether the controls assigned to a given operational area are implemented,
 are operating as intended,
 and are producing the expected outcome.
 Self-assessments supplement —
 but do not replace —
 the internal audit and control testing activities defined in Sections 6.1 and 6.3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall conduct or coordinate self-assessments on a quarterly cadence.
 Each quarterly self-assessment cycle shall cover the policies and controls designated in the Annual Audit Plan for that quarter.
 Where the Annual Audit Plan designates a policy for self-assessment rather than internal audit,
 the quarterly self-assessment constitutes the annual assessment obligation for that policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Each self-assessment shall evaluate,
 at minimum:
 whether the required controls are documented and current,
 whether the controls have been executed within the cadences defined in the governing policy,
 and whether evidence of control execution exists in the System of Engagement or the applicable system of record.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall document self-assessment results in a work order in the System of Engagement in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Knowledge Management Policy).
 Each self-assessment record shall include:
 the policy or control area assessed,
 the assessment date,
 the controls evaluated,
 the determination for each control (conforming,
 observation,
 or deficiency as defined in Section 6.5),
 and any recommended actions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Where a self-assessment reveals a condition that requires deeper evaluation,
 the Assistant IT Director shall escalate the finding to the IT Director with a recommendation to initiate an unplanned internal audit or control test of the affected area.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Control Testing and Validation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Control testing validates that a specific technical or procedural control produces its intended security or operational outcome when exercised.
 Control testing goes beyond self-assessment by directly exercising the control mechanism rather than evaluating documentation and evidence of prior execution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall maintain a Control Testing Register in the System of Engagement.
 The register shall list each testable control,
 the governing policy,
 the testing method,
 the testing cadence,
 and the date and result of the most recent test.
 The register is a living instrument;
 the Assistant IT Director shall update it as policies are added,
 revised,
 or retired under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Policy Review and Update Procedures).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall select testing methods appropriate to the control being tested.
 Testing methods shall include one or more of the following:
 examination of documentation,
 records,
 or configuration artifacts;
 interview of personnel responsible for the control's operation;
 and direct testing through observation,
 execution,
 or simulation of the control mechanism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Each control test shall document:
 the control tested and the governing policy reference,
 the testing method used,
 the expected outcome,
 the actual outcome,
 the pass or fail determination,
 and any anomalies or observations noted during the test.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Testing cadence shall be risk-informed and shall comply with the following minimum frequencies:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Controls implementing CJIS Security Policy requirements shall be tested no less than annually.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Controls identified as high-risk under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 shall be tested no less than annually.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
All other controls shall be tested no less than once every twenty-four (24) months.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director may establish more frequent testing cadences for specific controls based on risk conditions,
 regulatory changes,
 or prior test failures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Where a control test results in a failure,
 the Assistant IT Director shall classify the finding per Section 6.5 and route it accordingly.
 The Assistant IT Director shall retest a failed control after remediation is complete;
 the retest result shall be documented in the same work order chain as the original test.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Audit Execution and Documentation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall conduct internal audits in accordance with the Annual Audit Plan or under IT Director authorization for unplanned assessments.
 Each internal audit shall follow a consistent methodology comprising four stages:
 scoping,
 evidence collection,
 analysis,
 and reporting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Scoping
\series default
:
 The auditor shall define the controls under assessment,
 the assessment criteria,
 the evidence to be collected,
 and the systems or records to be examined.
 The auditor shall retain the scoping document with the audit record.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Evidence Collection
\series default
:
 The auditor shall gather sufficient evidence to support a determination of control effectiveness.
 Evidence may include system configurations,
 log records,
 work order histories,
 training records,
 policy acknowledgment records,
 and direct observation of operational procedures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Analysis
\series default
:
 The auditor shall evaluate collected evidence against the requirements of the governing policy and applicable framework controls to determine whether each assessed control is conforming,
 warrants an observation,
 or constitutes a deficiency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Reporting
\series default
:
 The auditor shall prepare an audit summary that documents the scope,
 methodology,
 evidence collected,
 findings by control,
 and recommended actions.
 The auditor shall submit the audit summary to the IT Director within fifteen (15) business days of the completion of evidence collection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Objectivity is a core requirement of the audit function.
 Personnel shall not serve as the primary auditor for controls they materially implement,
 administer,
 or routinely operate.
 Where staffing constraints make full independence impractical,
 the IT Director shall document the constraint and ensure that audit results receive independent review.
 For the purposes of this policy,
 independent review means review by a person who did not participate in the implementation,
 operation,
 or assessment of the controls under evaluation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall evaluate the need for external assessment services when internal objectivity cannot be achieved for CJIS-relevant controls,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy CA-2(1) and CA-7(1).
\end_layout

